  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Food and Non-food Items Support By Unconditional Cash Assistance to Recent Armed Conflict IDPs in Kandahar, Hilmand, Uruzgan and Zabul Provinces.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is proposed based on second strategic objective of Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP) for 2016 as well as contributing for achieving of protection cluster objective 2 and NFI objective 1 &#x2013; confined in HRP for 2016. The provision of cash-based emergency for food and non-food items also contribute to the Nutrition objective 3 of HRP for 2016, as the cash will immediately enable the vulnerable families to have food in emergencies for two months.
The project title is &#x2013; emergency food and non-food items support by unconditional cash assistance to recent armed conflict IDPs in Kandahar, Hilmand, Uruzgan and Zabul provinces, and the overall objective of the project is to promote well-being of recent armed conflict IDPs as well as enabling them by unconditional cash assistance to meet immediate survival needs for food and non-food items in emergencies.
The proposed project will target the vulnerable beneficiaries in need of food and non-food items in the following areas of the target provinces where large number of recent IDPs are living:
Kandahar:
 Dand District
 Mayand District
 Shahwalikot District
 Khakriz District
 Zhari District
Hilmand:
 Lashkargah
 Garmsir District
 Nahr-e-Siraj District
 Nawa-I-Barakzayi District
 Nad Ali/Marjah District
Uruzgan:
 Tirin Kot
 Dehrawood district
 Chora/Chinarto district
Zabul
 Qalat
 Shahjoy district
 Shinkai district
 Arghandab district
The more crucial issue is the accessibility to these areas, because security constraints has acted as main barriers for delivery of humanitarian assistance thus, most of the International organization and donor agencies are unable to approach the needy population in these areas due to their security protocols while HRDA has long existence in the region, is very familiar with local, political, social and security contexts of these areas and is very long experienced in terms of humanitarian assistance delivery in these areas, can approach to vulnerable families in emergencies, assessing and targeting them by cash-based food and non-food items assistance.
Throughout the course of the project it is planned that:
 14,000 individuals will be directly benefited from this project.
 2000 recent armed conflict IDP families receive cash-based assistance for food and non-food items</narrative>
  </description>
